===Etymology===
Recorded since c.1340, as "discharge of semen other than during sex," later, "desecration, defilement" (1382), from Late {{etyl|la|en}} [[pollutio]] "defilement," from Latin [[polluere]] "to soil, defile, contaminate", itself from [[por-]] "before" + [[-luere]] "to smear" (related to lutum "mud" and to [[lues]] "filth", compare Greek (''lyma'') "filth, dirt, disgrace" and (''lymax'') "rubbish, refuse," Old Irish [[loth]] "mud, dirt," Lithuanian [[lutynas]] "pool, puddle"). Meaning "make physically foul" is from 1540s. Sense of "contamination of the environment" first recorded c.1860,  but not common until c.1955

